**rare, review species in NM. Pics, audio. Late submission because I needed to use my computer to look at spectrogram. General vicinity of bird was (34.5124693,-103.1775665), and I mostly saw it on the W and SW edges of the small lake there, but it was tough to stay on, at least in the middle of the day. Very brown bird, so pale underneath that I picked it out visually as I arrived and then sat there for almost 2 hours, as I waited for it to call (I cut off checklist time before I left because I wasn’t really birding during this period. About half, or a bit more of lower mandible was orange. Very well defined upper wing bar, very different overall tone compared to adjacent Wood-pewees. While these individual traits are all subject to quite a range of variation, the fact that all observed visible were pretty comfortably within the typical of range of Eastern, and some were really pushing acceptability for Western, like the pale underbelly, lack of much vesting, and super well defined upper wingbar, basically the same brightness as the lower one, led me to think it was an Eastern from the start. The call, attached, is clear, rising, and not burry. I heard it make a longer call once, and really wish I could have gotten an audible recording, but the bird was too far away at the time and my phone didn’t pick it up, which was disappointing. After sending this around some, i see really no reason to suspect that this bird was anything but a pure EWPE, (though, as always, commentary welcome if anyone has differing thoughts- please feel free to email me). For an example of this more uncommon call type, see: https://macaulaylibrary.org/asset/261720871#_ga=2.200294509.2128276044.1600465260-405413718.1536424526. I know of no instances of WEWP making calls that are that clean, rising, and without any burriness, and went thru most of the WEWP calls on Macaulay to see if I could find one, which I could not.

Observation Details: Continuing - first found and documented by Steve Lewis on 4 July, followed by many others over the next week (sound recordings and photos). The attached images illustrate the changes in appearance of the underparts color (whiteness or dinginess) and lower mandible color (bright yellow orange to dingy orange) depending on the sun light or shadows under the tree canopy. In addition to the obvious vocalizations (reminded me of summer days growing up in Ohio), this individual showed most of the 'field marks' noted in guides: in particular an all yellowish lower mandible, both wingbars being of equal whiteness, bright white contrasting throat, and the primary extension appearing (when lucky enough to get a profile photo) longer than the tail extension.

Observation Details: I tried adding this species in the field, but was unable to.  This bird, found earlier today by Nicole K and Kris M. was gone when I got there, but briefly reappeared starting about 2:22 pm near large pines at rhe southeastermost corner, disappearing a few minutes later, after  vocalizing one or twice.   . Like Western wood-pewee but with all, (or mostly all--I could not see any dusky tip) pale  lower mandible, gray- olive-y back , pale washed out breast with not much of a vested look at all. In some photos  appears vested with a narrow 'river of white, with 'vest' extending the length of body, whereas WWPEs vest more distinct and more restricted to the breast and upper body.  Tertial edges and wing bars looked brighter than  most all Western Wood-pewees i have seen and similar brightness.   Vocalized  briefly once with upslurred stuttery  Purweeee call , sounding clearer and less burry than a western wood pewee,  which also usually has a distinct dark vest, and mostly darkish lower bill,   and with more of brownish gray back rather than green. Media notes: THE pewee.
Observation Details: Continuing *mega since yesterday morning (9/16) when it was first positively identified by Kahle/Sieburth. Appears to be the 4th MRN county record and 17th CA record. Located easily by its near constant calls and hawking from various perches in the large cypress closest to the residence.  Wood-Pewee by size, nondescript grayish above and pale below with whitish wingbars, a hint of dark vest and long pp (versus empidonax flycatchers). While not entirely diagnostic by themselves, a combination of features such as lighter breast (than WEWP); bright, nearly all orange lower mandible with only a dark tip; and calls (dry "plit" and whistled, slightly rising "pawee") supports the identification as EAWP over the very similar WEWP. Calls of both species during migration and winter can be strikingly similar.

We learned of a possible EAWP from Tom Miko during a pelagic trip aboard the Navegante this morning.  After the return of the boat to King Harbor, and following lunch, we proceeded to Dominguez Park where a small crown of birders, including some who also had been on the Navegante, had already staked out a location where both EAWP and WEWP were being seen.  The WEWP appeared almost immediately after we arrived and, after about 10 minutes, the bird believed to an EAWP soon appeared, perching high in a eucalyptus and engaging in typical flycatching behavior.  The bird had the dusky "vest," weak eyering, long tail and long primary projections characteristic of a wood-pewee.  Generally, the bird was almost identical to the WEWP, but we did notice that the bird had paler throat and more yellow on the lower mandible than the WEWP, and its back appeared (to me at least) more of an olive-gray hue rather than the dull gray you see on the back of a WEWP.  Also, the double wingbars appeared to be broader and more conspicuous than is typically seen on a WEWP.  I did not see the secondaries well enough to note whether the bird had the whiter feather edgings typical of EAWP.  The bird was observed by some through scopes and was photographed and sound-recorded by multiple birders.  Poor photos of mine will be attached.
Continuing 2nd county record found yesterday by Loren Wright.

Still in extreme SE corner of FRNC. Almost right away heard faint call outside fence at northern corner. Seemed far off but call is faint. Believe now it was just the other side of the bushes over the fence, out of view, most of the time. No playback used. At about 1720 it came into view of it own accord. Snuck in and perched on top strand of barbed wire mostly. Briefly disappeared back over fence out of view with occasional calls to reassure it was still close. Then stealthy reappearance on the wire again. One unusual foray (judging from the posts) to the cluster of very dense canopied pines close to road in this sector, but that was brief. From there, back to the corner. (I noticed it would call after changing position so I would hit record on my phone when it moved.) It was in view on and off for about an hour, and still there when I left.

Observation Details: Continuing - first found and documented by Steve Lewis on 4 July, followed by many others over the next week (sound recordings and photos). The attached images illustrate the changes in appearance of the underparts color (whiteness or dinginess) and lower mandible color (bright yellow orange to dingy orange) depending on the sun light or shadows under the tree canopy. In addition to the obvious vocalizations (reminded me of summer days growing up in Ohio), this individual showed most of the 'field marks' noted in guides: in particular an all yellowish lower mandible, both wingbars being of equal whiteness, bright white contrasting throat, and the primary extension appearing (when lucky enough to get a profile photo) longer than the tail extension.

Very long primary projection, yellow base of lower mandible indicate EWPe. One of the birds is not vested, and has bright wing bars and a faint eye ring, which may infact be an empid/willow, but the primary projections are still very long (i.e. probable EWPe).

Observation Details: Continuing bird found today by T. Miko. Grayish-olive back, wings, tail and head. Pale belly with possible light yellow wash in the middle and light gray wash on sides. Whitish wing-bars. Upper mandible dark gray. Lower mandible appeared to be completely light orange. O/A very similar to a Western Wood-Pewee. Vocalized many times with a fluid pah-wee call. Very different than Western Wood-Pewee’s more buzzy call.

Found by Tom Miko early this morning, when I (we, since the pelagic trip emptied out here once we returned to the dock) arrived, it had been seen and heard recently in the trees between the park and the fenced maintenance yard at the SE end. After a little wait, a pewee appeared, then a second. Both were exhibiting typical pewee behavior of flycatching from treetops and returning to perches with a quick post-landing tail quiver. One was clearly a dingy WWPE, but the other was paler below with an orange lower mandible and a more contrasting wing pattern, basically what an EWPE should look like. It did eventually begin calling and called several times, a clear, whistled pee-o-wee, like Eastern and unlike the buzzy call of Western or Western’s clearer single toned or descending whistle. I managed a recording on my phone, but others with better gear no doubt obtained better recording and photos.  MS: After seeing and hearing the bird from below/outside the east end of the park, went into the park and got some closer looks (but usually at awkward angles through foliage) and more audio recordings.  Saw EAWP catch and eat a dragonfly.  Bird would call many times in a row and then it would remain silent for an extended period.  Favored the eucalyptus along the eastern edge of the park, but occasionally visited the southern edge of the park.

Observation Details: Along Laguna Madre. A cryptic species replacing the almost identical Western Wood-Pewee in Eastern North America. Other than range, they can be distinguished by a combination of song and calls. The throat, lower mandible and underwing coverts average paler on Eastern but with some overlap. A useful field mark barely visible here are the white marginal coverts (leading edge of the folded wing). These whitish edges are not present on Western Wood-Pewee.

My husband (Brian B. Dunn) spotted what he thought was a  flycatcher species while walking dog and came to get me.  Took photos. Think it is an Eastern Wood-Pewee.  Would fly off and return to the same two perches. at the upper forested edge of a ravine with running water (Arroyo Abreu). I have to add that in October 2019 I was walking around in that area and I remember hearing a bird , in the very early morning and in that same general area of this observation, that sounded to me like an Eastern Wood-Pewee. I had just moved here from Massachusetts and was quite familiar with Eastern Wood-Pewee vocalizations. As I was not familiar with the species in the Dominican Republic I figured maybe it was some local species. Have to monitor more closely this area which I have avoided due to construction/development and its accompanying forest edge destruction.

Possibility this is actually a Western Wood-Pewee. Heard calling 2x and call  matched Sibleys call for western. Lots of photos taken. We tried recording the sound but were unsuccessful except for a very short clip.  The Wood-Pewee was observed for 26 min by 5 of us. It made several sallies to catch insects landing near the same location each time. It was heard calling two times uttering a single short call unlike any Eastern Wood-Pewee  calls we had heard. After the first call, Ken checked the Sibleys Western Wood-Pewee calls and it was a really good match. Later checking xeno-canto I found an EAWP recording taken Dec 25, 1996 in Venezula that reminds me of what we heard (XC232665) but  not as close as the Sibleys western calls. Unless the  photos show some distinctive western feature, I will list as an EAWP, the more expected species.

Observation Details: A small flycatcher was seen perched on a dead pine snag at 8:35 am. Initial ID was pewee with possibility of Willow Flycatcher. We watched for 5+ minutes as it sat; no vocalizations and no movement except for head. Wings and tail/tail coverts not visible. Bird left the perch and flew NE and landed high up in a tall pine. See images 337, 338. On our return to the parking lot, a second small flycatcher was seen high up in a pine along the trail. Although considerably more distant, this bird also appeared to be an Eastern Wood Pewee, based on profile, primary and tail length,  primary extension and bill shape and extent of yellow lower mandible. Tail coverts were not visibly spotted, although the view is not good. Images 354 and 382. While this may represent a second, distinct, pewee, examination of a map showed the two observations were about 100 yds apart in a straight line. Since both birds behaved similarly, sitting still for extended periods, perched high on exposed bare branches, and after sallying, returned to same or very close to same perch, I expect the two sightings are of the same individual.

**3rd county record. Audio and photos of lower mandible. Seen on backside of Mendoza flycatching making its way towards the direction of Nunes. Made a “purrreee” call twice and audio obtained for the second time it called. Lots of photos taken with 100-400 mm lens and one photo (obtained by Noah Arthur) showed the extremely yellow lower mandible with an inkling of black at the tip. First seen next to a Western Wood Pewee and showed how much lighter in color the Eastern was compared to the Western. Also noticed the pale breast and flanks which stood out from what a Western would typically portray. Also noticed two bold white wingbars which an Eastern is supposed to have. It also had a very limited eye ring which can be displayed in both Eastern and Western Wood Pewee’s. The throat was very white and contrasted the grayish head and mantle. The vent on the Eastern was also very white and did not have any streaking or grayish coloring at all. The tail position was also angled downward from the wingtips which a Western Wood Pewee doesn’t really do that often.  The cheek was also very pale in comparison to a Western which usually has a very dark cheek which blends in to its mantle and head. Controversy over this bird but according to reputable sources this bird is an Eastern Wood Pewee, however, no conclusion has been made yet. Opinions are still flowing in and audio and photos are being sent to the East coast for opinions as well.

Heard one across the marsh, singing the characteristic "pee-a-wheeeee" song. The other was very bold, allowing me to get within about 4-5 feet and seeming to follow me as I walked. Media notes: adults continually feeding from gravestones, planted saplings, and low branches from mature trees, making regular visits to feed nestlings.
Observation Details: They have been feeding hatchlings for the last week to 10 days. An adult was seen incubating newly hatched birds (based on the adults position on the nest) about 10 days ago, then around the same time seen regurgitating into small unseen chicks sitting well below the rim of the nest.   Now, it is a rapid-fire feeding from both adults, averaging about 1 feeding/minute between them, oftentimes one leaving at the same time the other arrives. The nestlings must be growing fast, demanding noticeably more fuel daily.  It is difficult to observe these birds at the nest due to the nest being surrounded by leaves (requiring the adults to mostly enter from below, less often from above or horizontally). The only time the nest itself can be see/photographed from our perspective is during wind gusts when glimpses occur occasionally as the branch sways and bounces.   There have been no BHCOs seen around at all. The only external challenge for the EAWP adults has been keeping a fox squirrel from coming down the sloping branch toward the nest - they have very aggressively discouraged that notion, successfully so far.

Continuing from yesterday (6/9); a first county record, remarkably stumbled across by Tom M on his way to his pelagic!! Thanks, Tomas, and congrats on a beautiful find!! :)) And special thanks to Andy B for doing the heavy lifting and re-finding it and alerting us of its location, the same morning!! Thanks, Andy!! :))   Similar in structure to its Western Wood-Pewee (WEWP) buddy but overall lighter and with light greenish-gray hues with lighter underparts contrasted against a light gray, less distinct vest; equal in brightness on the wingbars against dark wings in comparison to the grayish/subtle wingbars of a WEWP; orange lower mandible that’s almost entirely orange compared to the darker orange lower mandible (75-80% of the bill) that blends from the base to a darker tip on a WEWP; when close to one another, the Eastern Wood-Pewee (EAWP) seemed to be bolder/robust in the chest and less slender than the WEWP. Unfortunately, I was not able to discern any differences in the wing proportions this time around.   1213 to 1400ish – I walked up to a tall Euc, in the SE corner of the park (33.8563303, -118.3759968), and saw it sitting, just waiting patiently for me, perched on a leafless lower branch. I’ve been fortunate to have observed a couple of these guys this past week, so as soon as I saw the bright wingbars, the orange lower mandible, and its light underparts, I took a couple pics of the silent Pewee and sent them over to Curtis and Loren, and confirmed my suspected ID, before blasting it out on WhatsApp. I continued to observe it, playing around with the nearby WEWP which was a trip because the two of them would swap perches, and play tricks on me. However, their playful shenanigans forced me to hone into their different characteristics as one would swap with the other. Both naturally had the same flycatching activity, sallying out of its perch, and return to it. I waited for it to vocalize and attempted to get a recording, but the construction in the park, along with the commotion of children in the schools nearby, was all against me. Luckily, when I later returned to look for the Rose-breasted Grosbeak reported earlier today, I heard the EAWP calling, halfway from the main parking lot to its tree, but this time, with the WEWP perched below it on a separate branch. Wow!! Great comparison in coloration and surprisingly, size. But even better, Omar and I saw both of them sitting on the same branch, right next to one another, no more than 6in apart!! I guess we were both engrossed in staring at them via bins that we both missed out on an epic photo op (lol). Anyways, the EAWP was more vocal overall than the WEWP, however, the WEWP did vocalize a much softer one-syllable call, “peeew”.

Found by Tom Miko early this morning, when I (we, since the pelagic trip emptied out here once we returned to the dock) arrived, it had been seen and heard recently in the trees between the park and the fenced maintenance yard at the SE end. After a little wait, a pewee appeared, then a second. Both were exhibiting typical pewee behavior of flycatching from treetops and returning to perches with a quick post-landing tail quiver. One was clearly a dingy WWPE, but the other was paler below with an orange lower mandible and a more contrasting wing pattern, basically what an EWPE should look like. It did eventually begin calling and called several times, a clear, whistled pee-o-wee, like Eastern and unlike the buzzy call of Western or Western’s clearer single toned or descending whistle.  [NS: After seeing the bird from the lower level high up in the eucalyptus, I joined Mark, Janet, Chef Ito, Chris, Curtis, Dave P, Chezy, Ken, Loren and others at the upper level to better listen to and look at the bird. Several people mentioned clear differences in plumage between this bird and Western Wood-Pewees. All I will say is that I do not share their confidence with my perhaps more limited knowledge of these species (fairly familiar with Western here and usually see Easterns on occasional visits to the east coast), and I would not attempt to identify this bird if it were silent. Once identified by call, we could look for differences in plumage and try to convince ourselves that they were significant...   The lower mandible was the most obvious difference compared to a Western Wood-Pewee nearby: it was entirely pink with almost no dark, as opposed to this particular Western which had pink towards the base blending to a dirty blackish towards the tip. The wingbars were bold, including the upper wingbar - but I spent an hour staring at a Western Wood-Pewee yesterday and that bird had two bright wingbars as well. The underparts were brighter on this bird, with a weaker vest, and looking more creamy than the dingy underparts of a Western. With the views I had, I could not confidently say anything about the proportions of the wings and tail (other than that it was an obvious Wood-Pewee). Against backlit cloudy skies, I would likewise hesitate to say anything more about color patterns as well.  The call was very obviously an Eastern Wood-Pewee however, and I got multiple recordings, attached. Again, I had spent an hour listening to a Western Wood-Pewee making clear whistled calls the previous day (not the normal burry calls). That clear Western Wood-Pewee call was perhaps a little more elongated than normal for that species, but still shorter than this Eastern Wood-Pewee and not rising as much as this bird. The Eastern Wood-Pewee spectrogram has a bathtub shape, compared to the opposite, slightly convex shape of the clear call of a Western Wood-Pewee.  Happy to see one in LA county, after I could not bring myself to go to a different county in the past couple of days just to see a bird that basically looks identical to our Wood-Pewees.]

The wingbars were bold, including the upper wingbar - but I spent an hour staring at a Western Wood-Pewee yesterday and that bird had two bright wingbars as well. The underparts were brighter on this bird, with a weaker vest, and looking more creamy than the dingy underparts of a Western. With the views I had, I could not confidently say anything about the proportions of the wings and tail (other than that it was an obvious Wood-Pewee). Against backlit cloudy skies, I would likewise hesitate to say anything more about color patterns as well.  The call was very obviously an Eastern Wood-Pewee however, and I got multiple recordings, attached. Again, I had spent an hour listening to a Western Wood-Pewee making clear whistled calls the previous day (not the normal burry calls). That clear Western Wood-Pewee call was perhaps a little more elongated than normal for that species, but still shorter than this Eastern Wood-Pewee and not rising as much as this bird. The Eastern Wood-Pewee spectrogram has a bathtub shape, compared to the opposite, slightly convex shape of the clear call of a Western Wood-Pewee.  Happy to see one in LA county, after I could not bring myself to go to a different county in the past couple of days just to see a bird that basically looks identical to our Wood-Pewees.]

Observation Details: Along Laguna Madre. A cryptic species replacing the almost identical Western Wood-Pewee in Eastern North America. Other than range, they can be distinguished by a combination of song and calls. The throat, lower mandible and underwing coverts average paler on Eastern but with some overlap. A useful field mark barely visible here are the white marginal coverts (leading edge of the folded wing). These whitish edges are not present on Western Wood-Pewee.

Observation Details: This bird had me looking twice and more. Flags rare for late, and my initial thinking was that this bird had a good possibility for an off-track western empid, several species of which I have never seen and most of which I have absolutely minimal experience with. Ultimately I think the primary projection wins the day, but I nonetheless wanted to get this up quickly, and I'm not 100% certain. This bird spent much of its time un-pewee-like lurking inside trees, hunting from interior branches and so forth; it seemed much grayer overall to me than typically browner pewee; it has quite a clean and contrasting whitish throat in many views; chest minimally vested, really more gray-tinged than any real pewee-like vest.  OTOH In favor of the pewee i.d: apparently dusky light grizzling to the undertail coverts; long enough (I think) somewhat scimitar-like primary projection; almost no meaningful eye-ring; wingbars buff-tinged; bird at times indeed favoring exposed perches to which it intermittently returned. (Lower mandible seen well despite my being on my own roof and shooting down on the bird; quite orange at base, almost black to tip half. Gape orange. "Capped" appearance best seen in photos 4 and 5, with gray cap gently contrasting with face.) [A talented consultant finds nothing amiss with the Eastern Wood Pewee I.D.]

Observation Details: photo upload pending. Bird was perched on a fairly high bare limb tip. The flycatcher we observed last Friday and debated over as either an eastern wood pewee or an acadian flycatcher was flagged by Ebird. Flycatchers can be tough to ID. Lewis provided a good photo. After further research using Sibley’s and Natl. Geographic field guides to compare to the photo, I agree with the ebird monitor that the bird we saw is an eastern wood pewee. The pewee is larger, and lacks the full eye ring of an acadian. Its wing bars are less distinct than the acadian’s. The bill color is tricky as lighting and coloration can vary,  but the pewee has a dark upper mandible and a dull yellow/orange lower mandible.

Observation Details: I note the mandible is not as flagrantly pale as a typical Pewee, the head is  more rounded, also the tail seems shorter and the body not as slender as a Peewee. The bird was sallying forth from a perch about 5' off the ground - not higher as I had typically seen Peewees. Seen at the Cove at the NW corner of Baseball Field no. 4. Ruben Stoll and Charlie Muise reviewed this and in addition to the length of the primaries, you can see the fault bar across the tail, which makes it highly likely this is a hatch-year bird, and possibly a rather young one.  Also, there is virtually no eyering.  “I don't see any Empid in this” per Charlie Muise.
Photos

Possibility this is actually a Western Wood-Pewee. Heard calling 2x and call  matched Sibleys call for western. Lots of photos taken. We tried recording the sound but were unsuccessful except for a very short clip.  The Wood-Pewee was observed for 26 min by 5 of us. It made several sallies to catch insects landing near the same location each time. It was heard calling two times uttering a single short call unlike any Eastern Wood-Pewee  calls we had heard. After the first call, Ken checked the Sibleys Western Wood-Pewee calls and it was a really good match. Later checking xeno-canto I found an EAWP recording taken Dec 25, 1996 in Venezula that reminds me of what we heard (XC232665) but  not as close as the Sibleys western calls. Unless the  photos show some distinctive western feature, I will list as an EAWP, the more expected species.
